-- FACTBOX: Societe Generale reports 4.9 bln-euro fraud
-- 
-- Thu Jan 24, 2008 6:04am EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/01/24/us-socgen-factbox-idUSL2455227420080124

 

 (Reuters) - Societe Generale has uncovered a fraud by one of its traders which will have a 4.9 billion-euro ($7.16-billion) hit on its 2007 results, France's second-largest listed bank said on Thursday. 

 Following are some background details on the bank and what it had to say about the situation. * The bank said the trader behind the fraud was based in Paris and involved in futures hedging on European equity market index in 2007 and 2008. The bank alleges he used in-depth knowledge of the control procedures resulting from his former employment in the middle office to hide his positions. * Societe Generale was founded in 1864 under Napoleon III. It set up a permanent office in London in 1871. It is now present in 77 countries and employs 120,000 people. * Societe Generale had a market capitalization of 36.9 billion euros as of Wednesday's Paris market close. * The bank serves 22.5 million customers in France and worldwide. * As of June 2007, it was the fourth largest bank in the eurozone with 467 billion euros in assets under management. * Societe Generale is planning to raise 5.5 billion euros in fresh capital to strengthen its balance sheet. The capital increase has already been underwritten. * The bank also announced further writedowns of 2.05 billion euros related to the global credit crunch. * SocGen board rejected a proposal by Chairman and Chief Executive Daniel Bouton to resign. (Reporting Astrid Wendlandt; Editing by Greg Mahlich)